==Old English==

===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*mainjan'', from Indo-European ''*mein-, *moin-'' ‘intention, opinion’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[mena|mēna]] ‘signify’, Old Saxon [[menian|mēnian]] (Dutch [[meenen]] ‘intend, make known’), Old High German [[meinen]] (German [[meinen]] ‘have an opinion’).  The IE root is also the source of Old Irish [[mían]] ‘wish, desire’, Old Church Slavonic [[мӗнити]] (Polish [[mienić]] ‘signify, believe’).  Sense 5 may be a separate word.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'mæ:nan/

